tions. Organized around environments rather than particular locations, the book includes geological overviews and descriptions of common plants and animals. Lynch also explains the landscape’s environmental history as well as the effects of centuries of human interventions and the growing fallout from climate change. This indispensable guide not only brings the Connecticut River’s ecology and pivotal role in American history to life but instills a deeper appreciation for the river’s diverse and abundant beauty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aEcologyzConnecticut RivervGuidebooks. 0aEstuarine animalszConnecticut RivervGuidebooks. 0aWetland animalszConnecticut RivervGuidebooks. 0aWetland ecologyzConnecticut RivervGuidebooks. 0aWetland plantszConnecticut RivervGuidebooks. 7aNATURE / Ecosystems & Habitats / Rivers.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074979340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300277548?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300277548423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300277548/original  a978-3-11-074979-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles